<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,439,464]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Leaf mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[347,484,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–82" captionStartId="109.[151,264,1660,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@109.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="109" captionText="FIGURES 75–82. leaf mines; 75: Agromyza reptans Fallén in Urtica dioica; 76: Agromyza rudbeckiana Scheffer &amp; Lonsdale in Heliopsis helianthoides; 77: same, secondary mine; 78: Agromyza soka spec. nov. in Robinia pseudoacacia; 79: Agromyza vockerothi Spencer in Rubus sp.; 80: Agromyza sp. 1 in Ƒerbesina alternifolia; 81: Japanagromyza viridula (Coquillett) in Quercus alba; 82: J. viridula in Q. ilicifolia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452935/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs. 81–82</figureCitation>
) 
<collectingRegion box="[502,522,440,464]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">A</collectingRegion>
brownish blotch, or sometimes irregularly linear, with frass in irregular lumps. Because mines are formed in leaves that are still expanding, the oviposition site and associated feeding punctures often open into conspicuous holes, and the mined portion of the leaf is disfigured. The mines on 
<taxonomicName box="[1237,1388,511,536]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[1237,1388,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Quercus alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had distinct primary and secondary feeding lines (
<figureCitation box="[663,746,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–82" captionStartId="109.[151,264,1660,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@109.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="109" captionText="FIGURES 75–82. leaf mines; 75: Agromyza reptans Fallén in Urtica dioica; 76: Agromyza rudbeckiana Scheffer &amp; Lonsdale in Heliopsis helianthoides; 77: same, secondary mine; 78: Agromyza soka spec. nov. in Robinia pseudoacacia; 79: Agromyza vockerothi Spencer in Rubus sp.; 80: Agromyza sp. 1 in Ƒerbesina alternifolia; 81: Japanagromyza viridula (Coquillett) in Quercus alba; 82: J. viridula in Q. ilicifolia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452935/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
