<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,620,645]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[361,422,620,644]" name="United States of America" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">USA</collectingCountry>
: GA, IN, KS, MA, ME, NC, *OK, PA, SC, TN, VA; 
<collectingCountry box="[1039,1128,620,645]" name="Canada" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Canada</collectingCountry>
: NS, ON; 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1388,620,645]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
. We have also seen photographed leaf mines from IL and NJ. 
<bibRefCitation box="[821,1151,655,680]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref103475" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Stegmaier, C. E. Jr. (1973) Agromyzidae of Florida with a supplement on species from the Caribbean. Arthropods of Florida and Neighboring Land Areas, 7, 1 - 205." type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Stegmaier (1973)</bibRefCitation>
state that it is “virtually certain” that the Puerto Rican specimens mentioned in the original description represent another species, but the basis for this assertion is unclear.
</paragraph>
